# Context Save After Commits

After every `git commit` (whether you initiated it or the user asked), generate or update the file `CONTEXT.md` in the project root.

## What to include

```markdown
# Project Context — Virtual Analyst

> Last updated: <ISO date-time of commit>
> Commit: <short hash> — <commit message first line>
> Branch: <current branch>

## Architecture

<Brief summary of the tech stack and project structure. Keep to 5-10 lines.>

## Recent Changes (this commit)

<Bullet list of what changed in this commit — files, features, fixes. 3-10 bullets.>

## Current State

<What is working, what is deployed, what feature flags are active.>

## In Progress / Next Steps

<Anything left incomplete, planned next phases, known issues. Bullet list.>

## Key Files & Patterns

<List the most important files/directories a new agent should read first to understand the codebase. 5-15 entries.>

## Conventions

<Summarise coding conventions: language version, frameworks, testing approach, DB access pattern, error handling, etc. Bullet list.>
```

## Rules

- Always overwrite `CONTEXT.md` (not append). Each save is a full snapshot.
- Keep it under 120 lines. Be concise — this is a handoff doc, not a changelog.
- Do NOT include secrets, API keys, or .env values.
- Do NOT block the commit to write this file. Write it immediately after the commit succeeds, then `git add CONTEXT.md && git commit --amend --no-edit` to include it in the same commit (only if the commit was just created by you and has not been pushed yet). If the commit was already pushed, create a separate small commit for the context save.
- If multiple commits happen in one session, only generate the context save after the final commit before the conversation ends or the user moves on.
